</head>
<body>
    <main>
        <h1>LeetCode <%= problemNumber %>: <%= problemTitle || 'Problem ' + problemNumber %> (C++)</h1>
        <div class="problem-description">
            <p><strong>Problem:</strong>
                <%= problemDescription || 'Problem description will be loaded here.' %>
            </p>
            <p><strong>Example:</strong>
                <%= example || 'Example will be loaded here.' %>
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="code-container">
            <button class="copy-button" onclick="copyCode(this)">Copy Code</button>
            <pre><code class="language-cpp">class Solution {
public:
    // Follow-up of LC 153: the array may now contain DUPLICATES.
    // Still find the minimum in as few comparisons as possible.
    //
    // The same binary search logic from LC 153 applies, but duplicates
    // introduce one ambiguous case:
    //
    //   nums[mid] == nums[hi]
    //
    // When this happens we cannot determine which half contains the minimum.
    // Example:
    //   [3, 1, 3, 3, 3]  →  mid=2: nums[2]=3 == nums[4]=3
    //   The minimum (1) is in the LEFT half, but the right half also starts with 3.
    //   We cannot safely move lo or collapse hi to mid.
    //
    // Safe resolution: shrink hi by 1 (hi--).
    //   - We never lose the minimum because nums[hi] == nums[mid],
    //     so even if nums[hi] were the minimum, nums[mid] is an identical copy.
    //   - Worst case (all duplicates): O(n). Average case: O(log n).
    //
    // The three cases:
    //   nums[mid] &gt; nums[hi]  →  pivot in right half  →  lo = mid + 1
    //   nums[mid] &lt; nums[hi]  →  right half sorted, min at mid or left  →  hi = mid
    //   nums[mid] == nums[hi] →  ambiguous, safely shrink right  →  hi--
    //
    // Time : O(log n) average, O(n) worst case (all duplicates)
    // Space: O(1)

    int findMin(vector&lt;int&gt;&amp; nums) {
        int lo = 0, hi = (int)nums.size() - 1;

        while (lo &lt; hi) {
            int mid = lo + (hi - lo) / 2;

            if (nums[mid] &gt; nums[hi]) {
                // Minimum is strictly in the right portion (excluding mid)
                lo = mid + 1;
            } else if (nums[mid] &lt; nums[hi]) {
                // Right half is sorted; minimum is at mid or further left
                hi = mid;
            } else {
                // nums[mid] == nums[hi]: ambiguous — safely drop hi
                // (nums[hi] is a duplicate of nums[mid], so we lose nothing)
                hi--;
            }
        }

        // lo == hi: converged on the minimum element
        return nums[lo];
    }
};</code></pre>
